{"title":"Does declining fertility lower the gender pay gap?","link":"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/907833374/0/marginalrevolution~Does-declining-fertility-lower-the-gender-pay-gap.html","date":1731518132000,"content":"<blockquote><p>Using a descriptive decomposition and data from the Panel Study of Income Dynamics, we show that, in gross terms, fertility decline can explain almost one-quarter of gender pay convergence from 1980 to 2018. Even net of a host of controls for human capital and job characteristics, fertility decline explains 8 percent of the attenuation of the US gender pay gap 1980–2018—about half as much as changes in education and about a quarter as much as changes in full-time work experience and job tenure combined. Finally, we show that employees’ fertility decline was fastest in the 1980s and subsequently slowed; this, in conjunction with persistent gender differences in parenthood–wage associations, helps explain stalled progress toward gender pay parity.</p></blockquote>\r\n<p>That is from <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://academic.oup.com/sf/advance-article-abstract/doi/10.1093/sf/soae153/7862688\" target=\"_blank\">a newly published article</a> by Alexandra Killewald and Nino José Cricco.  Via the excellent <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.nationalaffairs.com/blog/detail/findings-a-daily-roundup/equity-stakes\" target=\"_blank\">Kevin Lewis</a>.</p>\r\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2024/11/does-declining-fertility-lower-the-gender-pay-gap.html\">Does declining fertility lower the gender pay gap?</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com\">Marginal REVOLUTION</a>.</p>\r\n<img height=\"1\" width=\"1\" src=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/i/907833374/0/marginalrevolution\" />\r\n<div><a href=